^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Okay, let's first discuss the 2N opener. It is somewhat similar to a couple of hands ago where I opened 2C followed by 2N and I think 2N has some merit. However, in this case I personally would probably have opened 1D. I felt the previous hand was too strong to open 1D with 22 HCP. In tht hand, although I was 2-2 in the majors, I had stoppers in both majors. This hand has several flaws for opening 2N, although as I said, 2N is certainly a very plausible bid. The major flaw is that one of the doubleton majors is unstopped. I am not saying you can't open 2N with a small doubleton. But since you have 2 doubletons, I think it is a tad more dangerous.|
PG| ***** 95 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The second flaw is it is off shape for a 2N bid. Therefore, because of those flaws, I might choose 1D, but 2N was ok.  Now, as to the play. Eddy can count 4 clubs, 1 spade, 2 hearts, and 1 diamond for sure. That is 8 tricks. He has 2 plays for a 9th trick. and with careful play he can try for both alternatives. Although unfortunately niether happen to work. But, the best way to play the hand is to play AK of clubs first. If clubs are 3-2, he now has 2 club dummy entries. One alternative is to hope North has the Ace of diamonds. If that fails, alternative 2 is the spade finesse. He can play the Jack of clubs to the Queen, such that the 8 of clubs is another dummy entry and then play a diamond.|
