^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|In general, Eddy made a very nice 4S bid, and had the right idea on the play. Let's talk about the auction first. Eddy has 2 choices over 1H, 1S or 2H (Michaels). You can argue for either. With a six card spade suit, overcalling 1S has merit. But 2H gets your shape across. However, it does not do justice to your point count as Michaels is often done with a weak hand. So, one could make a case for either 1S or 2H. |
PG| ***** 114 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|3H by Nada was fine and it gave me a problem. I technically have 10 dummy points but my King of hearts is dubious. If it were in any other suit it would clearly be much better. However, I wanted to encourage Eddy to bid 4S over 4H, so I decided to bid 3S, even though I am a bit weak given that my King is in hearts. |
PG| ***** 115 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, as to whether Kerrie should bid 4H. The only reason not to bid 4H is tactical--she doesn't want us to bid 4S. By the law, they have a 10 card fit, so 4H is fine. The argument for passing is not that 4H is a bad contract (because by the law it is not). The argument against bidding 4H is that it might push us into 4S where we otherwise might play 3S. On competitive auctions in general, that is something you need to be aware of.|
PG| ***** 116 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|I am very wary of bidding 4 of a minor over their major suit. Not because I think 4 of the minor is going down but because I might push them into a making game. That is something tactical you need to think about. A bridge saying is "the 3 level belongs to the opponents." That means, it is ok to compete to the 3 level, but you need to be careful when competing to the 4 level.|
PG| ***** 117 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now, as to the play. Eddy played the diamond suit very well. The way he played it, if Kerrie ducks the diamond, he can assume East has the King and play the 10. His way of playing the suit gives him the best chance of discovering the best way to play the suit. |
PG| ***** 118 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|However, I would like to suggest a couple of adustments to the play. At trick five once Kerrie leads a spade, ducking was fine. But on the next spade, he should overtake the 9 with the Queen in hand and ruff a diamond. He can then ruff a heart, draw trump, and claim, losing a club, no matter how diamonds are split. |
